rena, too, according to some evidence","format":"article","time":{"pretty":"Nov. 21, 2014","published":"2014-11-21 11:00:35","updated":"2014-11-21 16:00:35","minute":"11:00 am","short":"11\/21"},"authors":[{"id":213517826,"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/author\/sarah-begley\/","name":"Sarah Begley","bio":"Sarah Begley is Digital Operations Editor for TIME.com.","short_bio":"","types":[],"twitter":"SCBegley","twitter_url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/SCBegley","gplus":"117345536491513403348","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":"http:\/\/i2.wp.com\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/03\/mg_3363.jpg?crop=248px%2C118px%2C2684px%2C2684px&resize=100%2C100","contributor":false}],"content":"<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-related\" data-name=\"rr-related\"><div class=\"read-more-inline related\"><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3592888\/new-hunger-games-mockingjay-clip\/\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-video data-event=\"rr-related\"><img src=\"\" alt=\"\" title=\"\"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h\">More<\/h6><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title\">New <i>Hunger Games: Mockingjay<\/i> Clip Shows District 8 Under Fire<\/h3><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3587635\/snl-jennifer-lawrence-taylor-swift-hunger-games-blank-space\/\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-video data-event=\"rr-related\"><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title\"><i>Hunger Games<\/i> Cast Parodies Taylor Swift&#8217;s &#8216;Blank Space&#8217; on <i>SNL<\/i><\/h3><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p>Katniss Everdeen returns to the big screen Friday in <em>The Hunger Games: Mockingjay Part 1<\/em>, and though she left the arena behind at the end of <em>Catching Fire<\/em>, she&rsquo;s still a gladiator at heart.<\/p>\n<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-partner\" data-name=\"rr-partner\"><div class=\"read-more-list\"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h\">More<\/h6><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3600706\/jennifer-lawrence-sing-mockingjay\/\" class=\"read-more-list-article\" data-event=\"rr-more\">Hear Jennifer Lawrence Sing in Mockingjay<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3599607\/imitation-game-accuracy-benedict-cumberbatch-alan-turing\/\" class=\"read-more-list-article\" data-event=\"rr-more\">The History Behind Benedict Cumberbatch&#8217;s <i>The Imitation Game<\/i><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/storyline\/michael-brown-shooting\/pair-suspected-trying-acquire-bombs-ferguson-protests-n254021?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">Feds Suspect Pair Sought Bombs for Ferguson Protests <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/news\/crime-courts\/ohio-men-wrongly-convicted-murder-after-39-years-released-n253356?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">Two Ohio Men Wrongly Convicted of Murder Walk Free <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/news\/us-news\/fsu-shooter-myron-may-left-message-i-do-not-want-n253436?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">FSU Shooter Left Message: 'I Do Not Want to Die in Vain' <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p>Or rather, a gladiatrix.<\/p>\n<p>It turns out there is some historical evidence that women may indeed have fought in the Roman games&mdash;though not necessarily alongside their male peers, as Katniss does in the Hunger Games, and likely not with such high stakes.<\/p>\n<p>Kathleen M. Coleman, Professor of Classics at Harvard University, says there are accounts of the emperors staging gladiatorial spectacles in which women also participated, and that a decree of the Senate from A.D. 19 forbade both male and female descendants of the upper class from participating in such spectacles. &ldquo;This doesn&rsquo;t <em>prove<\/em> that women were fighting as gladiators,&rdquo; she says, &ldquo;but it suggests that the society was afraid that they might want to.&rdquo;<\/p>\n<p>More famously, a marble bas relief sculpture from between the first and second century A.D. depicts two gladiatrices in battle, with an inscription saying they fought to a draw. They are named Achillia, the feminine form of Achilles, and Amazon, the name of a group of mythical female fighters. It was common for gladiators to adopt epic stage names after their favorite heroes.<\/p>\n<figure class=\"inline-portrait_small_2x\"><img src=\"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/female-gladiators.jpeg?w=560\" alt=\"Roman civilization, Relief portraying fight between female gladiators\" \/><figcaption class=\"image-caption\"><span class=\"credit\">Dea \/ A. Dagliorti&mdash;De Agostini\/Getty Images<\/span><\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>Since neither woman died in the fight, the sculpture is clearly not an epitaph, so Coleman says it might have been &ldquo;something put up in a gladiatorial barracks,&rdquo; where the fighters lived separately from civilians, &ldquo;commemorating the sort of greatest hits of that barracks.&rdquo;<\/p><div class=\"content-ad\" id=\"content-ad-3598421\"><\/div>\n<p>Like Katniss, gladiatrices likely had humble beginnings. While some gladiators did choose of their own volition to take on the profession and thus enter the lowest rung of the social ladder, the majority were slaves. Those who did volunteer were likely in it either for the valor or to escape debts&mdash;after all, as Coleman says, &ldquo;if you can&rsquo;t own, then you can&rsquo;t owe.&rdquo;<\/p>\n<p>Is that really so different from the Girl on Fire, the volunteer from District 12 who sacrifices herself to pay her sister&rsquo;s debt?<\/p>\n<p>There were many types of gladiators, and each type came with its own weapons, armor and moves. You sometimes might see two styles pitted against each other, Coleman says. &ldquo;So the one style might be very heavily armed and protected, and will therefore be relatively impregnable&mdash;but slow. The opponent might be very scantily armed, and therefore very fast and unencumbered, but vulnerable. These kinds of pairings seem to have interested Romans.&rdquo;<\/p>\n<p>Katniss might have been at ease in the arena with her weapon of choice: the Sagittarius gladiator was known for using a bow and arrow.<\/p>\n<p>Unlike the young combattants in the Hunger Games, the gladiators didn&rsquo;t usually fight to the death. Though &ldquo;occasionally a very poor performance might result in the gladiator losing his life,&rdquo; Coleman says, losers would often be sent back for more training, and might even have the option to retire.<\/p>\n<p>The odds may not have been <em>ever<\/em> in their favor, but they sure got a better deal <a href=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=a-ins2kYZqQ\">than Rue<\/a>.<\/p><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-ad\" data-name=\"rr-ad\"><div class=\"right-rail-ad\" id=\"right-rail-ad-3598421\"><\/div><\/aside><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-share\" data-name=\"rr-share\"><span class=\"social-links\">\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-mail social-link-mail\" href=\"mailto:?subject=The%20Real-Life%20Hunger%20Games%3A%20Meet%20the%20Ancient%20Women%20Who%20Lived%20Like%20Katniss%20%7C%20TIME&body=The%20Real-Life%20Hunger%20Games%3A%20Meet%20the%20Ancient%20Women%20Who%20Lived%20Like%20Katniss%0A%0AWomen%20may%20have%20battled%20in%20the%20Roman%20arena%2C%20too%2C%20according%20to%20some%20evidence%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3598421%2Freal-female-gladiators%2F\" data-event=\"email\" title=\"Click to Email this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-fb social-link-fb popup\" href=\"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/sharer\/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3598421%2Freal-female-gladiators%2F\" data-event=\"fb-share\" title=\"Click to post this article to Facebook\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-tw social-link-tw popup\" href=\"#\" data-href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/intent\/tweet?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwp.me%2Fp5HMd-f673&text=Katniss%20Everdeen%20and%20the%20real%20history%20of%20female%20gladiators&via=TIMEHistory\" data-event=\"tweet\" title=\"Click to Tweet this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-linkedin social-link-linkedin popup\" href=\"http:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/shareArticle?mini=true&url=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3598421%2Freal-female-gladiators%2F&title=The+Real-Life+Hunger+Games%3A+Meet+the+Ancient+Women+Who+Lived+Like+Katniss\" data-event=\"linkedin\" title=\"Click to post this article to LinkedIn\"><\/a>\n    <a href=\"#\" class=\"time-icons time-icons-comment toggle-comments\" data-lf-site-id=\"314099\" data-lf-article-id=\"3598421\" data-url=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3598421\/real-female-gladiators\/\" data-title=\"The Real-Life Hunger Games: Meet the Ancient Women Who Lived Like Katniss\" title=\"Click to view and post comments\" data-event=\"comment-click\">0<\/a>\n<\/span>\n<\/aside>","section":{"name":"History","slug":"history","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/history\/","description":"The news in context, from the archives of TIME. A historical view on breaking news, entertainment, media coverage, anniversaries, births, deaths and more"},"tag":{"name":"movies","slug":"movies","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/tag\/movies\/"},"tags":"Jennifer Lawrence|Mockingjay Part 1|movies|The Hunger Games","hero":{"class":"landscape","thumbnail":"http:\/\/i1.wp.com\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/hunger-games-mockingjay2.jpg?crop=915px%2C22px%2C897px%2C897px&resize=100%2C100","src":{"small":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/hunger-games-mockingjay2.jpg?w=280","small_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/hunger-games-mockingjay2.jpg?w=560","large":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/hunger-games-mockingjay2.jpg?w=550","large_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/hunger-games-mockingjay2.jpg?w=1100"},"credit":"Murray Close\u2014Lionsgate","caption":"","alt":"Hunger Games Mockingjay","providers":[]},"id":3598421,"encoded_url":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3598421%2Freal-female-gladiators%2F","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Fwp.me%2Fp5HMd-f673","encoded_title":"The+Real-Life+Hunger+Games%3A+Meet+the+Ancient+Women+Who+Lived+Like+Katniss","twitter_text":"Katniss%20Everdeen%20and%20the%20real%20history%20of%20female%20gladiators","twitter_via":"TIMEHistory","related_posts":[{"id":3592888,"title":"New <i>Hunger Games: Mockingjay<\/i> Clip Shows District 8 Under Fire","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3592888\/new-hunger-games-mockingjay-clip\/","format":"video","paid":false,"edit_link":null,"contributor":false,"short_title":"New <i>Hunger Games: Mockingjay<\/i> Clip Shows District 8 Under Fire","hero":false},{"id":3587635,"title":"<i>Hunger Games<\/i> Cast Parodies Taylor Swift's 'Blank Space' on <i>SNL<\/i>","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3587635\/snl-jennifer-lawrence-taylor-swift-hunger-games-blank-space\/","format":"video","paid":false,"edit_link":null,"contributor":false,"short_title":"<i>Hunger Games<\/i> Cast Parodies Taylor Swift's 'Blank Space'"}],"subjects":[null],"ads":{"neg":"false","post_title":"The Real-Life Hunger Games: Meet the Ancient Women Who Lived Like Katniss"},"Partner_Module":{"partner":"Select","post_title":"The Real-Life Hunger Games: Meet the Ancient Women Who Lived Like Katniss"},"email_title":"The%20Real-Life%20Hunger%20Games%3A%20Meet%20the%20Ancient%20Women%20Who%20Lived%20Like%20Katniss%20%7C%20TIME","email_body":"The%20Real-Life%20Hunger%20Games%3A%20Meet%20the%20Ancient%20Women%20Who%20Lived%20Like%20Katniss%0A%0AWomen%20may%20have%20battled%20in%20the%20Roman%20arena%2C%20too%2C%20according%20to%20some%20evidence%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3598421%2Freal-female-gladiators%2F","omniture":{"modules":"rr-related|rr-partner|rr-ad|rr-share"},"outbrain":{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3598421\/real-female-gladiators\/","widget_id":"AR_6","hide":false}},{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3598069\/obama-immigration-lincoln-fdr\/","shortlink":"http:\/\/wp.me\/p5HMd-f61n","title":"Is Obama Overreaching on Immigration? Lincoln and FDR Would Say &#8216;No&#8217;","friendly_title":"Is Obama Overreaching on Immigration? Lincoln and FDR Would Say \u2018No\u2019","post_type":"post","available":true,"time_article":true,"comments_allowed":true,"short_title":"Is Obama Overreaching on Immigration? Lincoln and FDR Would Say &#8216;No&#8217;","excerpt":"Like Lincoln and Roosevelt before him, Obama occupies the White House in a time of great crisis","format":"article","time":{"pretty":"Nov. 21, 2014","published":"2014-11-21 10:15:18","updated":"2014-11-21 15:15:18","minute":"10:15 am","short":"11\/21"},"authors":[{"id":291634461,"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/author\/david-kaiser\/","name":"David Kaiser","bio":"","short_bio":"","types":[],"twitter":"","twitter_url":"","gplus":"","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":null,"contributor":false}],"content":"<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-related\" data-name=\"rr-related\"><div class=\"read-more-inline related\"><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3597981\/obamas-executive-action-immigration\/\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-article data-event=\"rr-related\"><img src=\"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/171435251.jpg?w=560&#038;h=374&#038;crop=1\" alt=\"US-POLITICS-IMMIGRATION-OBAMA\" title=\"President Barack Obama meets with business leaders on immigration reform on June 24, 2013 in the Roosevelt Room of the White House in Washington, DC. \"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h\">More<\/h6><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title\">Obama&#8217;s Executive Action on Immigration Will Tear Us Apart<\/h3><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3596143\/immigration-jorge-ramos-univision\/\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-article data-event=\"rr-related\"><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title\">Univision&#8217;s Jorge Ramos Calls Obama&#8217;s Immigration Actions a &#8216;Triumph For The Latino Community&#8217;<\/h3><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p>Last night, President Obama announced new steps that will allow about five million undocumented immigrants to obtain work permits and feel free of imminent deportation. Given that we now have an estimated 10&ndash;11 million such people within our nation and that many of them clearly will never leave, this seems a reasonable first step towards giving them all some kind of legal status. But, because of the anti-immigration stance of the Republican Party, which will entirely control Congress starting on Jan. 3, the President will have to base this step solely on executive power. And even before the President spoke, various Republicans had accused him of acting like an <a href=\"http:\/\/www.weeklystandard.com\/blogs\/sessions-obama-now-emperor-united-states_819614.html\">emperor<\/a> or a <a href=\"http:\/\/www.politico.com\/magazine\/story\/2014\/11\/president-obama-is-not-a-monarch-113028.html#.VG3x68lGXAE\">monarch<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/www.usatoday.com\/story\/news\/politics\/2014\/11\/19\/usa-today-capital-download-with-tom-coburn\/19263969\/\">warning of anarchy and violence<\/a> if he goes through with his plans.<\/p>\n<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-partner\" data-name=\"rr-partner\"><div class=\"read-more-list\"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h\">More<\/h6><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3599394\/bill-cosby-accusers-cosby-show-fans\/\" class=\"read-more-list-article\" data-event=\"rr-more\">Ask an Ethicist: Can I Still Watch The Cosby Show?<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3598207\/bill-cosby-rape-accusations-silence\/\" class=\"read-more-list-article\" data-event=\"rr-more\">Bill Cosby, Camille Cosby and the Oppressive Power of Silence<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/storyline\/michael-brown-shooting\/pair-suspected-trying-acquire-bombs-ferguson-protests-n254021?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">Feds Suspect Pair Sought Bombs for Ferguson Protests <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/news\/crime-courts\/ohio-men-wrongly-convicted-murder-after-39-years-released-n253356?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">Two Ohio Men Wrongly Convicted of Murder Walk Free <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/news\/us-news\/fsu-shooter-myron-may-left-message-i-do-not-want-n253436?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">FSU Shooter Left Message: 'I Do Not Want to Die in Vain' <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p>There are, in fact, substantial legal and historical precedents, including a recent Supreme Court decision, that <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nytimes.com\/roomfordebate\/2014\/11\/18\/constitutional-limits-of-presidential-action-on-immigration-12\/proposed-executive-orders-would-continue-focus-on-immigration-priorities\">suggest<\/a> that Obama&#8217;s planned actions would be neither unprecedented nor illegal. This is of course the President&rsquo;s own position, that no extraordinary explanation is needed&mdash;yet we can also put his plans in the broader context of emergency presidential powers, which in fact have a rich history in times of crisis in the United States. It is not accidental that this issue of Presidential power is arising now, because it will inevitably arise&mdash;as the founders anticipated&mdash;any time a crisis has made it unusually difficult to govern the United States. Like Abraham Lincoln and Franklin Roosevelt, Obama occupies the White House in a time of great crisis, and therefore finds it necessary to take controversial steps.<\/p>\n<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-mag\" data-name=\"rr-mag\"><div class=\"read-more-inline magazine has-cover\"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h read-more-popular\">Popular Among Subscribers<\/h6>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"popular-lead\"><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3547827\/the-art-of-science\/?pcd=pw-pas\"><img src=\"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/10\/timeinterstellarcover.jpg?w=560\" alt=\"\" title=\"\" data-loaded=\"true\"><\/a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3547827\/the-art-of-science\/?pcd=pw-pas\" class=\"read-more-article\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title time-icons time-icons-key\"><em>Interstellar<\/em>, Where No Movie Has Gone Before<\/h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href=\"https:\/\/subscription.time.com\/storefront\/subscribe-to-time\/link\/1019509.html\" class=\"subscribe-button\">Subscribe<\/a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3547825\/nucor-tries-to-reverse-decline-in-american-steelmaking\/?pcd=pw-pas\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-article><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title time-icons time-icons-key\">The Last Men of Steel<\/h3><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3547828\/review-interstellar-christopher-nolan\/?pcd=pw-pas\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-article><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title time-icons time-icons-key\">Review: <em>Interstellar\u2019s<\/em> Wonder of Worlds Beyond<\/h3><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p>The Founding Fathers distrusted executive authority, of course, because they had fought a revolution in the previous decade against the arbitrary authority of King George III. But, on the other hand, they had come to Philadelphia in 1787 because their current government, the early version of the U.S. system established by the Articles of Confederation, was so weak that the new nation was sinking into anarchy. So they created a strong executive and a much more powerful central government than the Articles of Confederation had allowed for&mdash;and having lived through a revolution, they also understood that governments simply had to exercise exceptional powers in times of emergency.<\/p>\n<p>They made one explicit reference to an emergency power, authorizing the federal government to suspend the right of habeas corpus&mdash;freedom from arbitrary arrest&mdash;&#8221;in cases of rebellion or invasion [when] the public safety may require it.&#8221; Nearly 80 years later, when the southern states had denied the authority of the federal government, Abraham Lincoln used this provision to lock up southern sympathizers in the North, and eventually secured the assent of Congress to this measure. He also used traditional powers of a government at war&mdash;including the confiscation of enemy property&mdash;to emancipate the slaves within the Confederacy in late 1862. With the help of these measures, the North won the war and the Union survived&mdash;apparently exactly what the Founders had intended.<\/p><div class=\"content-ad\" id=\"content-ad-3598069\"><\/div>\n<p>When Franklin Roosevelt took the oath of office in the midst of a virtual economic collapse in March of 1933, he not only declared that the nation had &#8220;nothing to fear but fear itself,&#8221; but also made clear that he would take emergency measures on his own if Congress did not go along. That spring, the country was treated to a remarkable movie, <em>Gabriel Over the White House<\/em>, in which the President did exactly that&mdash;but as it turned out, the Congress was more than happy to go along with Roosevelt&#8217;s initial measures. It wasn&rsquo;t until his second term that Congress turned against him; he, like Obama, used executive authority to find new means of fighting the Depression. In wartime he also claimed and exercised new emergency powers in several ways, including interning Japanese-Americans, this time without a formal suspension of habeas corpus. In retrospect both a majority of Americans and the courts have decided that some of these measures, especially the internment, were unjust and excessive, but the mass of the people accepted them in the midst of a great war as necessary to save the country, preferring to make amends later on. Though opponents continually characterized both Lincoln and FDR as monarchs and dictators trampling on the Constitution, those are judgments which history, for the most part, has not endorsed.<\/p>\n<p>As the late William Strauss and Neil Howe first pointed out about 20 years ago in their remarkable books, <em>Generations<\/em> and <em>The Fourth Turning<\/em>, these first three great crises in our national life&mdash;the Revolutionary and Constitutional period, the Civil War, and the Depression and the Second World War&mdash;came at regular intervals of about 80 years. Sure enough, just as they had predicted, the fourth such great crisis came along in 2001 as a result of 9\/11. President Bush immediately secured from Congress the sweeping authority to wage war almost anywhere, and claimed emergency powers to detain suspected terrorists at Guantanamo. (Some of those powers the Supreme Court eventually refused to recognize.) The war against terror was, however, only one aspect of this crisis. The other is the splintering of the nation, once again, into two camps with largely irreconcilable world views, a split that has paralyzed our government to an extent literally never before seen for such a long period. Immigration is only one of several problems&mdash;including climate change, inequality and employment&mdash;that the government has not been able to address by traditional means because the Republican Party has refused to accept anything President Obama wants to do.<\/p>\n<p>The Founders evidently understood that when the survival of the state is threatened, emergency measures are called for. We are not yet so threatened as we were in the three earlier crises, but our government is effectively paralyzed. Under the circumstances it seems to me that the President has both a right and a duty to use whatever authority he can find to solve pressing national problems. Congressional obstructionism does not relieve him of his own responsibilities to the electorate.<\/p>\n<p><em>David Kaiser, a historian, has taught at Harvard, Carnegie Mellon, Williams College, and the Naval War College. He is the author of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.historyunfolding.com\">seven books<\/a>, including, most recently, <\/em>No End Save Victory: How FDR Led the Nation into War<em>. He lives in Watertown, Mass.<\/em><\/p><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-ad\" data-name=\"rr-ad\"><div class=\"right-rail-ad\" id=\"right-rail-ad-3598069\"><\/div><\/aside><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-share\" data-name=\"rr-share\"><span class=\"social-links\">\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-mail social-link-mail\" href=\"mailto:?subject=Is%20Obama%20Overreaching%20on%20Immigration%3F%20Lincoln%20and%20FDR%20Would%20Say%20%E2%80%98No%E2%80%99%20%7C%20TIME&body=Is%20Obama%20Overreaching%20on%20Immigration%3F%20Lincoln%20and%20FDR%20Would%20Say%20%E2%80%98No%E2%80%99%0A%0ALike%20Lincoln%20and%20Roosevelt%20before%20him%2C%20Obama%20occupies%20the%20White%20House%20in%20a%20time%20of%20great%20crisis%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3598069%2Fobama-immigration-lincoln-fdr%2F\" data-event=\"email\" title=\"Click to Email this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-fb social-link-fb popup\" href=\"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/sharer\/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3598069%2Fobama-immigration-lincoln-fdr%2F\" data-event=\"fb-share\" title=\"Click to post this article to Facebook\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-tw social-link-tw popup\" href=\"#\" data-href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/intent\/tweet?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwp.me%2Fp5HMd-f61n&text=Opinion%3A%20Is%20Obama%20overreaching%20on%20immigration%3F%20Lincoln%20and%20FDR%20would%20say%20no&via=TIMEHistory\" data-event=\"tweet\" title=\"Click to Tweet this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-linkedin social-link-linkedin popup\" href=\"http:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/shareArticle?mini=true&url=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3598069%2Fobama-immigration-lincoln-fdr%2F&title=Is+Obama+Overreaching+on+Immigration%3F+Lincoln+and+FDR+Would+Say+%E2%80%98No%E2%80%99\" data-event=\"linkedin\" title=\"Click to post this article to LinkedIn\"><\/a>\n    <a href=\"#\" class=\"time-icons time-icons-comment toggle-comments\" data-lf-site-id=\"314099\" data-lf-article-id=\