"AR_6","hide":false}},{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3596139\/the-hunger-games-mockingjay-young-adult\/","shortlink":"http:\/\/wp.me\/p5HMd-f5wf","title":"How a 1960s Literary Trend Brought Us <i>The Hunger Games<\/i>","friendly_title":"How a 1960s Literary Trend Brought Us The Hunger Games","post_type":"post","available":true,"time_article":true,"comments_allowed":true,"short_title":"How a 1960s Literary Trend Brought Us <i>The Hunger Games<\/i>","excerpt":"Dystopian fiction used to be for adults","format":"article","time":{"pretty":"Nov. 20, 2014","published":"2014-11-20 21:00:05","updated":"2014-11-21 02:00:05","minute":"9:00 pm","short":"11\/20"},"authors":[{"id":208178771,"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/author\/lily-rothman\/","name":"Lily Rothman","bio":"Lily Rothman is Archive Editor of TIME.com.","short_bio":"","types":[],"twitter":"lilyrothman","twitter_url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/lilyrothman","gplus":"115083326003510988963","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":"http:\/\/i1.wp.com\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/01\/mg_2552.jpg?crop=364px%2C105px%2C2338px%2C2337px&resize=100%2C100","contributor":true}],"content":"<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-related\" data-name=\"rr-related\"><div class=\"read-more-inline related\"><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3592888\/new-hunger-games-mockingjay-clip\/\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-video data-event=\"rr-related\"><img src=\"\" alt=\"\" title=\"\"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h\">More<\/h6><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title\">New <i>Hunger Games: Mockingjay<\/i> Clip Shows District 8 Under Fire<\/h3><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3587635\/snl-jennifer-lawrence-taylor-swift-hunger-games-blank-space\/\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-video data-event=\"rr-related\"><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title\"><i>Hunger Games<\/i> Cast Parodies Taylor Swift&#8217;s &#8216;Blank Space&#8217; on <i>SNL<\/i><\/h3><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p>As Katniss &amp; Co. get ready to storm movie theaters this weekend with <em>Mockingjay<\/em>, the latest installment in <em>The Hunger Games<\/em> series, it may seem like a foregone conclusion that futuristic teenagers will have to battle an oppressive dystopian regime alongside their crushes.<\/p>\n<p>But it wasn&#8217;t always that way. As TIME&#8217;s Lev Grossman wrote back in 2012 while exploring the history of the teen romance-dystopia genre in books and movies, until the 1960s &mdash; notably, with the release of the <em>Tripod<\/em> series by Christopher Samuel Youd &mdash; dystopia wasn&#8217;t for teenagers. Books like <em>1984 <\/em>and <em>Brave New World<\/em> are seen as classics of grown-up literature; during the last 50 years, their analogues have usually been meant for teenagers.<\/p>\n<p>But that doesn&#8217;t mean that the genre hasn&#8217;t changed further during that half-century:<\/p>\n<blockquote><p><em>The Hunger Games<\/em> is every bit as grim as the <em>Tripod<\/em> books, but it also tells us a lot about how the future, and the present, has changed since the 1960s. Now we have a great tradition of strong female characters in young-adult fiction thanks to writers like Madeleine L&#8217;Engle, Judy Blume and Anne McCaffrey. And along with coed dystopias comes, inevitably, romance: it&#8217;s understood now that if you&#8217;re fighting to save the human race, you&#8217;re going to have to deal with a star-crossed crush at the same time. If the <em>Tripod<\/em> books were published today (they&#8217;ve been reissued with covers that make them look like novelizations of the boy&#8217;s-own science-fiction cartoon <em>Ben 10<\/em>), Will Parker would fall for a tough fellow resistance member with a fetching pageboy haircut over her mind-control cap. Or better yet, a Tripod would crack open and disgorge a nubile, sufficiently humanoid alienne.<\/p><\/blockquote>\n<p><em><strong>Read the full article here: <\/strong><\/em><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/vault\/issue\/2012-03-12\/page\/126\/\" target=\"_blank\">Love Among the Ruins<\/a><\/p><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-ad\" data-name=\"rr-ad\"><div class=\"right-rail-ad\" id=\"right-rail-ad-3596139\"><\/div><\/aside><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-share\" data-name=\"rr-share\"><span class=\"social-links\">\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-mail social-link-mail\" href=\"mailto:?subject=How%20a%201960s%20Literary%20Trend%20Brought%20Us%20The%20Hunger%20Games%20%7C%20TIME&body=How%20a%201960s%20Literary%20Trend%20Brought%20Us%20The%20Hunger%20Games%0A%0ADystopian%20fiction%20used%20to%20be%20for%20adults%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3596139%2Fthe-hunger-games-mockingjay-young-adult%2F\" data-event=\"email\" title=\"Click to Email this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-fb social-link-fb popup\" href=\"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/sharer\/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3596139%2Fthe-hunger-games-mockingjay-young-adult%2F\" data-event=\"fb-share\" title=\"Click to post this article to Facebook\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-tw social-link-tw popup\" href=\"#\" data-href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/intent\/tweet?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwp.me%2Fp5HMd-f5wf&text=How%20the%20teen%20dystopia%20genre%20got%20us%20to%20%27The%20Hunger%20Games%27&via=TIMEHistory\" data-event=\"tweet\" title=\"Click to Tweet this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-linkedin social-link-linkedin popup\" href=\"http:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/shareArticle?mini=true&url=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3596139%2Fthe-hunger-games-mockingjay-young-adult%2F&title=How+a+1960s+Literary+Trend+Brought+Us+The+Hunger+Games\" data-event=\"linkedin\" title=\"Click to post this article to LinkedIn\"><\/a>\n    <a href=\"#\" class=\"time-icons time-icons-comment toggle-comments\" data-lf-site-id=\"314099\" data-lf-article-id=\"3596139\" data-url=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3596139\/the-hunger-games-mockingjay-young-adult\/\" data-title=\"How a 1960s Literary Trend Brought Us &lt;i&gt;The Hunger Games&lt;\/i&gt;\" title=\"Click to view and post comments\" data-event=\"comment-click\">0<\/a>\n<\/span>\n<\/aside>","section":{"name":"History","slug":"history","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/history\/","description":"The news in context, from the archives of TIME. A historical view on breaking news, entertainment, media coverage, anniversaries, births, deaths and more"},"tag":{"name":"movies","slug":"movies","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/tag\/movies\/"},"tags":"Books|Dystopia|Katniss|movies|The Hunger Games","hero":{"class":"landscape","thumbnail":"http:\/\/i2.wp.com\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/hunger-games-mockingjay1.jpg?crop=1189px%2C119px%2C327px%2C326px&resize=100%2C100","src":{"small":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/hunger-games-mockingjay1.jpg?w=280","small_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/hunger-games-mockingjay1.jpg?w=560","large":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/hunger-games-mockingjay1.jpg?w=550","large_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/hunger-games-mockingjay1.jpg?w=1100"},"credit":"Murray Close\u2014Lionsgate","caption":"","alt":"Hunger Games: Mockingjay","providers":[]},"id":3596139,"encoded_url":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3596139%2Fthe-hunger-games-mockingjay-young-adult%2F","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Fwp.me%2Fp5HMd-f5wf","encoded_title":"How+a+1960s+Literary+Trend+Brought+Us+The+Hunger+Games","twitter_text":"How%20the%20teen%20dystopia%20genre%20got%20us%20to%20%27The%20Hunger%20Games%27","twitter_via":"TIMEHistory","related_posts":[{"id":3592888,"title":"New <i>Hunger Games: Mockingjay<\/i> Clip Shows District 8 Under Fire","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3592888\/new-hunger-games-mockingjay-clip\/","format":"video","paid":false,"edit_link":null,"contributor":false,"short_title":"New <i>Hunger Games: Mockingjay<\/i> Clip Shows District 8 Under Fire","hero":false},{"id":3587635,"title":"<i>Hunger Games<\/i> Cast Parodies Taylor Swift's 'Blank Space' on <i>SNL<\/i>","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3587635\/snl-jennifer-lawrence-taylor-swift-hunger-games-blank-space\/","format":"video","paid":false,"edit_link":null,"contributor":false,"short_title":"<i>Hunger Games<\/i> Cast Parodies Taylor Swift's 'Blank Space'"}],"subjects":[null],"ads":{"neg":"false","post_title":"How a 1960s Literary Trend Brought Us <i>The Hunger Games<\/i>"},"Partner_Module":{"partner":"Select","post_title":"How a 1960s Literary Trend Brought Us <i>The Hunger Games<\/i>"},"email_title":"How%20a%201960s%20Literary%20Trend%20Brought%20Us%20The%20Hunger%20Games%20%7C%20TIME","email_body":"How%20a%201960s%20Literary%20Trend%20Brought%20Us%20The%20Hunger%20Games%0A%0ADystopian%20fiction%20used%20to%20be%20for%20adults%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3596139%2Fthe-hunger-games-mockingjay-young-adult%2F","omniture":{"modules":"rr-related|rr-ad|rr-share"},"outbrain":{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3596139\/the-hunger-games-mockingjay-young-adult\/","widget_id":"AR_6","hide":false}},{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3597404\/mike-nichols\/","shortlink":"http:\/\/wp.me\/p5HMd-f5QE","title":"Mike Nichols: A Half-Century of Raves","friendly_title":"Mike Nichols: A Half-Century of Raves","post_type":"post","available":true,"time_article":true,"comments_allowed":true,"short_title":"How TIME Reviewed the Work of Mike Nichols","excerpt":"He was 'the sort of director whom most writers and actors only meet when they are asleep and dreaming'","format":"article","time":{"pretty":"Nov. 20, 2014","published":"2014-11-20 12:10:37","updated":"2014-11-20 17:10:37","minute":"12:10 pm","short":"11\/20"},"authors":[{"id":208178771,"url":"https:\/\/time.com\/author\/lily-rothman\/","name":"Lily Rothman","bio":"Lily Rothman is Archive Editor of TIME.com.","short_bio":"","types":[],"twitter":"lilyrothman","twitter_url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/lilyrothman","gplus":"115083326003510988963","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":"https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/01\/mg_2552.jpg?crop=364px%2C105px%2C2338px%2C2337px&resize=100%2C100","contributor":true}],"content":"<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-related\" data-name=\"rr-related\"><div class=\"read-more-inline related\"><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3597167\/mike-nichols-dies-career-in-photos\/\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-gallery data-event=\"rr-related\"><img src=\"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/birdcage.jpg?w=560&#038;h=374&#038;crop=1\" alt=\"\" title=\"&lt;i&gt;The Birdcage&lt;\/i&gt; (1996)\"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h\">More<\/h6><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title\">See Mike Nichols&#8217; Legendary Career in Photos<\/h3><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3597091\/mike-nichols-dead\/\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-video data-event=\"rr-related\"><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title\">Mike Nichols Dies at Age 83<\/h3><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p>When Mike Nichols, <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3597091\/mike-nichols-dead\/\" target=\"_blank\">who died on Wednesday at age 83<\/a>, first gained notice, it was not as a director. In 1958, Nichols, then 26, appeared along with his comedy partner Elaine May, on NBC&#8217;s <em>Omnibus <\/em>revue; within six months, the two were <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/vault\/issue\/1958-06-02\/page\/55\/\" target=\"_blank\">touted<\/a> by TIME as &#8220;the fastest-sharpening wits in television.&#8221; The two had met at the University of Chicago and began their dual career as sketch and improv comics in that city, as part of a group that would eventually feed into Second City.<\/p>\n<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-partner\" data-name=\"rr-partner\"><div class=\"read-more-list\"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h\">More<\/h6><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3598063\/mike-nichols-movies-remembrance-spamalot-the-graduate\/\" class=\"read-more-list-article\" data-event=\"rr-more\">Remembering Mike Nichols: Let&#8217;s Talk About Sex<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3597167\/mike-nichols-dies-career-in-photos\/\" class=\"read-more-list-article\" data-event=\"rr-more\">See Mike Nichols&#8217; Legendary Career in Photos<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/storyline\/michael-brown-shooting\/pair-suspected-trying-acquire-bombs-ferguson-protests-n254021?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">Feds Suspect Pair Sought Bombs for Ferguson Protests <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/news\/crime-courts\/ohio-men-wrongly-convicted-murder-after-39-years-released-n253356?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">Two Ohio Men Wrongly Convicted of Murder Walk Free <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/news\/us-news\/fsu-shooter-myron-may-left-message-i-do-not-want-n253436?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">FSU Shooter Left Message: 'I Do Not Want to Die in Vain' <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p>Though they were an instant hit on TV, the question of how to translate their comedy to the censored and scripted world on screen. They found their footing on Broadway instead with <em>An Evening with Mike Nichols and Elaine May,<\/em> which debuted in 1960. &#8220;<em>An Evening with Mike Nichols and Elaine May<\/em>,&#8221; TIME&#8217;s critic <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/vault\/issue\/1960-10-24\/page\/73\/\" target=\"_blank\">declared<\/a>, &#8220;is one of the nicest ways to spend one.&#8221; From that point on, the rave reviews just kept coming.<\/p>\n<p>By 1962, Nichols was acting in a play written by May, and in 1963 he directed <em>Barefoot in the Park, <\/em>earning <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/vault\/issue\/1963-11-01\/page\/78\/\" target=\"_blank\">another<\/a> rave: &#8220;If the theater housing this comedy has an empty seat for the next couple of years, it will simply mean that someone has fallen out of it. <em>Barefoot<\/em> is detonatingly funny.&#8221; He would <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3597288\/some-are-more-yossarian-than-others\/\" target=\"_blank\">later<\/a> tell TIME that it had been a turning point, the moment he realized he was meant to direct:<\/p>\n<blockquote><p>Nichols remembers: &ldquo;The first day of rehearsal, I knew, my God, this is <em>it<\/em>! It is as though you have one eye, and you&rsquo;re on a road and all of a sudden your eye lights up, and you look down and you know, &lsquo;I&rsquo;m an engine!&rsquo; &rdquo;<\/p><\/blockquote>\n<p>For his next Broadway foray, <em>Luv, <\/em>he earned the <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/vault\/issue\/1964-11-27\/page\/90\/\" target=\"_blank\">headline<\/a> &#8220;The Nichols Touch&#8221; and was called &#8220;the sort of director whom most writers and actors only meet when they are asleep and dreaming.&#8221; <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/vault\/issue\/1965-03-19\/page\/72\/\" target=\"_blank\">As for<\/a> 1965&#8242;s <em>The Odd Couple<\/em><em>, <\/em>&#8220;[t]he only worry they leave in a playgoer&#8217;s head is how to catch his breath between laughs.&#8221;<\/p><div class=\"content-ad\" id=\"content-ad-3597404\"><\/div>\n<p>In 1966, when he made his first foray into movies with <em>Who&#8217;s Afraid of Virginia Woolf?,<\/em> the performance he got out of star Elizabeth Taylor was <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/vault\/issue\/1966-07-01\/page\/94\/\" target=\"_blank\">deemed<\/a> &#8220;a sizeable victory.&#8221; By 1970, when he made a movie of <em>Catch-22<\/em>, he landed on the cover of the magazine, with a multi-page feature that praised the maturity of the work:<\/p>\n<blockquote><p>Fully loaded, the bombers take flight, make their lethal gyres and return empty. Under Nichols&rsquo; direction, the camera makes air as palpable as blood. In one long-lensed indelible shot, the sluggish bodies of the B-25s rise impossibly close to one another, great vulnerable chunks of aluminum shaking as they fight for altitude. Could the war truly have been fought in those preposterous crates? It could; it was. And the unused faces of the flyers, Orr, Nately, Aardvark, could they ever have been so young? They were: they are. <em>Catch-22<\/em>&lsquo;s insights penetrate the elliptical dialogue to show that wars are too often a children&rsquo;s crusade, fought by boys not old enough to vote or, sometimes, to think.<\/p><\/blockquote>\n<p>Despite his much-acclaimed career &mdash; which would continue for decades &mdash; not <em>every<\/em> one of his projects won applause.<\/p>\n<div class=\"video-wrapper\" data-pos=\"4\" data-continuous=\"1\"><object id=\"bc-video-3901278908001-4\" class=\"BrightcoveExperience\"><param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#000000\"><param name=\"width\" value=\"100%\"><param name=\"height\" value=\"100%\"><param name=\"playerID\" value=\"1847503743001\"><param name=\"isVid\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"isUI\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"dynamicStreaming\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"videoSmoothing\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"autoStart\" value=\"false\"><param name=\"linkBaseURL\" value=\"http:\/\/wp.me\/p5HMd-f5QE\"><param name=\"includeAPI\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"templateLoadHandler\" value=\"TIME_onTemplateLoad\"><param name=\"templateReadyHandler\" value=\"TIME_onTemplateReady\"><param name=\"wmode\" value=\"opaque\"><param name=\"htmlFallback\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"@videoPlayer\" value=\"3901278908001\"><\/object><\/div>\n<p>In 1967, for example, TIME gave one of his films <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/vault\/issue\/1967-12-29\/page\/59\/\" target=\"_blank\">a rare pan<\/a>. The picture in question &#8220;unfortunately shows his success depleted&#8221; because &#8220;[m]ost of the film has an alarmingly derivative style, and much of it is secondhand&#8221; with &#8220;a disappointing touch of TV situation comedy.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p>But, as befits a comedian by training, he had the last laugh: that movie was <em>The Graduate<\/em>.<\/p>\n<p><em><strong>Read the full cover 1970 story here, in TIME&#8217;s archives: <\/strong><\/em><a href=